# Read: Class 14 - Readings: Diversity & Inclusion in the Tech Industry

<h1>Reading</h1>

[That Time When Women Stopped Coding](That Time When Women Stopped Coding)

This article explains how modern comp sci is dominated by men. I discusses how the people who programmed the first digital computers were women. But then in 1984 something changed. It discusses how personal computers were entirely marketed to men and boys. Movies and media reinforced this. 



[Employee breakdown of key technology companies](https://informationisbeautiful.net/visualizations/diversity-in-tech/)

This was a chart from 2017. It is created to present imbalances between the general population and the employee breakdown of key tech companies in the ways of gender and ethnicity.


[Why diversity matters to your tech company](https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/columnist/2015/07/21/why-diversity-matters-your-tech-company/30419871/)

## Diverse teams are smarter and more creative

According to Scott E. Page, professor of complex systems, political science and economics at the University of Michigan: "Diverse groups of people bring to organizations more and different ways of seeing a problem and, thus, faster/better ways of solving it."

Intel, CEO Brian Krzanich has said: "A fully diverse and inclusive workplace is fundamental to our ability to innovate and deliver business results." A number of leaders we’ve spoken to are motivated by this research in their efforts to build the strongest, most innovative teams. 

## Diverse companies perform better

## Companies are losing out on great talent 

Everyone has a talent and something to offer. Companies need to make efforts to more boardly appeal and bring in the best talent. 

## Diverse companies can better serve a diverse user base 
People ofter build what they would like. The more diverse the people are at the company, the more diverse their products and services would be.


## It’s the right thing to do 

You should hire the best person for the job. 
